{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Although the success rate of fully automated generation remains to be improved, its potential as a semi-automated tool to assist developers has already been demonstrated [10].Horizontal Expansion across Ecosystems.",
    "To address the challenge of fragile generalization across different programming languages and domains, and to correct the methodological weakness of inadequate and narrow benchmarks, a key opportunity lies in horizontally expanding the application and evaluation of LLM-based testing to diverse software ecosystems.",
    "This requires validating and optimizing existing methods for a broader range of programming languages and specific application domains.",
    "While specialized research has shown promising results in languages such as C++ [17,170], Rust [28,30], and JavaScript [52,142], as well as in domains like gaming [107], finance [149], and high-performance computing [76], developing frameworks that are agnostic to language and domain remains a future goal.",
    "Similarly, in safety-critical domains such as autonomous driving software, research indicates that while foundational LLMs struggle with complex C++ codebases, their success rate in test generation can be significantly improved by incorporating deep static analysis, such as parsing build systems and call graphs, to provide precise context [140]."
  ],
